 The Blitzboks arrived in the French capital 25 points ahead of closest rivals Fiji in the standings on the back of four tournament wins and seven consecutive finals.With 22 points on offer for a tournament victory and just one round remaining, in London on May 20-21, SA clinched the title after third-placed England lost to Scotland before seeing off New Zealand 26-5 in their own semifinal.The Blitzboks were due to face Scotland in the final at the time of going to print.Said coach Neil Powell after his side were declared the world champions: "It's been an incredible season so far. We wanted to finish strong in this tournament and in London next week. Every time we put our jerseys on our backs we play for South Africa, for our family and people back home that support us. It's special for us. "